{{italic title}}
'''''Epistulae ad Atticum''''' ([[Latin language|Latin]] for "Letters to [[Titus Pomponius Atticus|Atticus]]") is a collection of letters from [[Ancient Rome|Roman]] politician and orator [[Cicero|Marcus Tullius Cicero]] to his close friend [[Titus Pomponius Atticus]]. The letters in this collection, together with Cicero's other letters, are considered the most reliable sources of information for the period leading up to the fall of the [[Roman Republic]]. The letters to Atticus are special among Cicero's works in that they provide a candid view into his personal character — containing confession, frank self-revelation, and a record of his moods from day to day, without alteration. Traditionally spanning 16 books, the collection features letters from 68 to 44&nbsp;BCE. A notable absence of early references to these particular letters suggest that they may not have been published until the middle of the first century CE, significantly later than Cicero's other letters and quite some time after the deaths of both Cicero (43&nbsp;BCE) and Atticus (32&nbsp;BCE).<ref>{{Cite book |editor-last=Shackleton Bailey |editor-first=D. R. |editor-link=D. R. Shackleton Bailey |date=April 1999 |title=Letters to Atticus |volume=I |url=http://www.loebclassics.com/view/LCL007/1999/volume.xml |publisher=Harvard University Press |access-date=5 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite EB1911|wstitle=Cicero}}</ref>

A manuscript containing the collection, along with ''[[Epistulae ad Quintum Fratrem]]'', and ''[[Epistulae ad Brutum]]'', was rediscovered in 1345 in [[Verona]] by [[Petrarch]].  Both the original and Petrarch's copy are lost, though a copy made for [[Coluccio Salutati]] is preserved in the [[Laurentian Library]] in [[Florence]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Cicero: Selected Letters |last=Abbott |first=Frank Frost |author-link=Frank Frost Abbott |date=1909 |publisher=Ginn and Co. |location=Boston |at=§68 |url=http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0076%3Atext%3Dintro%3Achapter%3D7}}</ref>

