'''''Smith v. State''''', [[Supreme Court of Alaska]] 614 P.2d 300 (1980), is a [[criminal case]] which distinguishes between the [[ALI test]] and the [[M'Naghten rule]] in an [[insanity defense]].<ref name=CL>''Criminal Law - Cases and Materials'', 7th ed. 2012, [[Wolters Kluwer Law & Business]]; [[John Kaplan (law professor)|John Kaplan]], [[Robert Weisberg]], [[Guyora Binder]], {{ISBN|978-1-4548-0698-1}}, [https://law.stanford.edu/publications/criminal-law-cases-and-materials-7th-edition/]</ref>{{rp|635–640}}

